interface-compositionevent.name: CompositionEvent
interface-compositionevent.summary: The DOM CompositionEvent represents events that occur due to the user indirectly entering text.
interface-compositionevent.title: CompositionEvent

event-type-keydown.name: keydown_event
event-type-keydown.summary: The keydown event is fired when a key is pressed.
event-type-keydown.title: Document: keydown event

event-type-keydown.name: keydown_event
event-type-keydown.summary: The keydown event is fired when a key is pressed.
event-type-keydown.title: Element: keydown event

event-type-keyup.name: keyup_event
event-type-keyup.summary: The keyup event is fired when a key is released.
event-type-keyup.title: Document: keyup event

event-type-keyup.name: keyup_event
event-type-keyup.summary: The keyup event is fired when a key is released.
event-type-keyup.title: Element: keyup event

event-type-wheel.name: wheel_event
event-type-wheel.summary: The wheel event fires when the user rotates a wheel button on a pointing device (typically a mouse).
event-type-wheel.title: Document: wheel event

event-type-wheel.name: wheel_event
event-type-wheel.summary: The wheel event fires when the user rotates a wheel button on a pointing device (typically a mouse).

ie.notes: Internet Explorer only exposes the wheel event via addEventListener; there is no onwheel attribute on DOM objects. See IE bug 782835.

event-type-wheel.title: Element: wheel event

event-type-auxclick.name: auxclick_event
event-type-auxclick.summary: The auxclick event is fired at an Element when a non-primary pointing device button (any mouse button other than the primary—usually leftmost—button) has been pressed and released both within the same element.

firefox.notes: Starting in Firefox 68, the auxclick event is used to trigger the new tab on middle-click action; previously, this had been done with the click event. Apps can prevent middle-click from opening new tabs (or middle-click to paste, if that feature is enabled) by intercepting auxclick on links, and auxclick event handlers can now open popups without triggering the popup blocker.

event-type-auxclick.title: Element: auxclick event

event-type-auxclick.name: onauxclick
event-type-auxclick.summary: The onauxclick property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an EventHandler for processing auxclick events.
event-type-auxclick.title: GlobalEventHandlers.onauxclick

event-type-blur.name: blur_event
event-type-blur.summary: The blur event fires when an element has lost focus. The main difference between this event and focusout is that focusout bubbles while blur does not.

firefox.notes: The interface for this event is Event, not FocusEvent.

firefox_android.notes: The interface for this event is Event, not FocusEvent.

event-type-blur.title: Element: blur event

event-type-blur.name: blur_event
event-type-blur.summary: The blur event fires when an element has lost focus.

firefox.notes: The interface for this event is Event, not FocusEvent.

event-type-blur.title: Window: blur event

event-type-click.name: click_event
event-type-click.summary: An element receives a click event when a pointing device button (such as a mouse's primary mouse button) is both pressed and released while the pointer is located inside the element.

firefox.notes: Beginning in Firefox 68, Firefox no longer incorrectly sends a click event for buttons other than the primary mouse button; previouly, there were circumstances in which this would occur. One example: middle-clicking a link would send a click to the document's <html> element.

event-type-click.title: Element: click event

event-type-compositionend.name: compositionend_event
event-type-compositionend.summary: The compositionend event is fired when a text composition system such as an input method editor completes or cancels the current composition session.
event-type-compositionend.title: Element: compositionend event

event-type-compositionstart.name: compositionstart_event
event-type-compositionstart.summary: The compositionstart event is fired when a text composition system such as an input method editor starts a new composition session.
event-type-compositionstart.title: Element: compositionstart event

event-type-compositionupdate.name: compositionupdate_event
event-type-compositionupdate.summary: The compositionupdate event is fired when a new character is received in the context of a text composition session controlled by a text composition system such as an input method editor.
event-type-compositionupdate.title: Element: compositionupdate event

event-type-dblclick.name: dblclick_event
event-type-dblclick.summary: The dblclick event fires when a pointing device button (such as a mouse's primary button) is double-clicked; that is, when it's rapidly clicked twice on a single element within a very short span of time.

firefox.notes: Starting in Firefox 68, dblclick events are only sent for the primary mouse button, per the specification.

event-type-dblclick.title: Element: dblclick event

event-type-error.name: error_event
event-type-error.summary: The error event is fired on an Element object when a resource failed to load, or can't be used. For example, if a script has an execution error or an image can't be found or is invalid.
event-type-error.title: Element: error event

event-type-error.name: error_event
event-type-error.summary: The error event is fired on a Window object when a resource failed to load or couldn't be used — for example if a script has an execution error.
event-type-error.title: Window: error event

event-type-focus.name: focus_event
event-type-focus.summary: The focus event fires when an element has received focus. The main difference between this event and focusin is that focusin bubbles while focus does not.

firefox.notes: The interface for this event is Event, not FocusEvent.

firefox_android.notes: The interface for this event is Event, not FocusEvent.

event-type-focus.title: Element: focus event

event-type-focus.name: focus_event
event-type-focus.summary: The focus event fires when an element has received focus.

firefox.notes: The interface for this event is Event, not FocusEvent.

event-type-focus.title: Window: focus event

event-type-focusin.name: focusin_event
event-type-focusin.summary: The focusin event fires when an element is about to receive focus. The main difference between this event and focus is that focusin bubbles while focus does not.
event-type-focusin.title: Element: focusin event

event-type-focusout.name: focusout_event
event-type-focusout.summary: The focusout event fires when an element is about to lose focus. The main difference between this event and blur is that focusout bubbles while blur does not.
event-type-focusout.title: Element: focusout event

event-type-mousedown.name: mousedown_event
event-type-mousedown.summary: The mousedown event is fired at an Element when a pointing device button is pressed while the pointer is inside the element.
event-type-mousedown.title: Element: mousedown event

event-type-mouseenter.name: mouseenter_event
event-type-mouseenter.summary: The mouseenter event is fired at an Element when a pointing device (usually a mouse) is initially moved so that its hotspot is within the element at which the event was fired.
event-type-mouseenter.title: Element: mouseenter event

event-type-mouseleave.name: mouseleave_event
event-type-mouseleave.summary: The mouseleave event is fired at an Element when the cursor of a pointing device (usually a mouse) is moved out of it.
event-type-mouseleave.title: Element: mouseleave event

event-type-mousemove.name: mousemove_event
event-type-mousemove.summary: The mousemove event is fired at an element when a pointing device (usually a mouse) is moved while the cursor's hotspot is inside it.
event-type-mousemove.title: Element: mousemove event

event-type-mouseout.name: mouseout_event
event-type-mouseout.summary: The mouseout event is fired at an Element when a pointing device (usually a mouse) is used to move the cursor so that it is no longer contained within the element or one of its children.
event-type-mouseout.title: Element: mouseout event

event-type-mouseover.name: mouseover_event
event-type-mouseover.summary: The mouseover event is fired at an Element when a pointing device (such as a mouse or trackpad) is used to move the cursor onto the element or one of its child elements.
event-type-mouseover.title: Element: mouseover event

event-type-mouseup.name: mouseup_event
event-type-mouseup.summary: The mouseup event is fired at an Element when a button on a pointing device (such as a mouse or trackpad) is released while the pointer is located inside it.
event-type-mouseup.title: Element: mouseup event

event-type-select.name: select_event
event-type-select.summary: The select event fires when some text has been selected.
event-type-select.title: Element: select event

idl-focusevent.name: relatedTarget
idl-focusevent.summary: The FocusEvent.relatedTarget read-only property is the secondary target, depending on the type of event:
idl-focusevent.title: FocusEvent.relatedTarget

interface-focusevent.name: FocusEvent
interface-focusevent.summary: The FocusEvent interface represents focus-related events, including focus, blur, focusin, and focusout.
interface-focusevent.title: FocusEvent

event-type-beforeinput.name: beforeinput_event
event-type-beforeinput.summary: The DOM beforeinput event fires when the value of an <input>, <select>, or <textarea> element is about to be modified. The event also applies to elements with contenteditable enabled, and to any element when designMode is turned on.
event-type-beforeinput.title: HTMLElement: beforeinput event

dom-inputevent-inputtype.name: inputType
dom-inputevent-inputtype.summary: The inputType read-only property of the InputEvent interface returns the type of change made to editible content. Possible changes include for example inserting, deleting, and formatting text.
dom-inputevent-inputtype.title: InputEvent.inputType

interface-inputevent.name: InputEvent
interface-inputevent.summary: The InputEvent interface represents an event notifying of editable content change.
interface-inputevent.title: InputEvent

dom-keyboardevent-keyboardevent.name: KeyboardEvent
dom-keyboardevent-keyboardevent.summary: The KeyboardEvent() constructor creates a new KeyboardEvent.
dom-keyboardevent-keyboardevent.title: KeyboardEvent()

dom-keyboardevent-code.name: code
dom-keyboardevent-code.summary: The KeyboardEvent.code property represents a physical key on the keyboard (as opposed to the character generated by pressing the key). In other words, this property returns a value that isn't altered by keyboard layout or the state of the modifier keys.
dom-keyboardevent-code.title: KeyboardEvent.code

dom-keyboardevent-iscomposing.name: isComposing
dom-keyboardevent-iscomposing.summary: The KeyboardEvent.isComposing read-only property returns a Boolean value indicating if the event is fired within a composition session, i.e. after compositionstart and before compositionend.
dom-keyboardevent-iscomposing.title: KeyboardEvent.isComposing

dom-keyboardevent-key.name: key
dom-keyboardevent-key.summary: The KeyboardEvent interface's key read-only property returns the value of the key pressed by the user, taking into consideration the state of modifier keys such as Shift as well as the keyboard locale and layout.

ie.notes: IE's implementation does not completely match the current spec because it is based on an older version of the spec.

dom-keyboardevent-key.title: KeyboardEvent.key

interface-keyboardevent.name: KeyboardEvent
interface-keyboardevent.summary: KeyboardEvent objects describe a user interaction with the keyboard; each event describes a single interaction between the user and a key (or combination of a key with modifier keys) on the keyboard.
interface-keyboardevent.title: KeyboardEvent

dom-mouseevent-buttons.name: buttons
dom-mouseevent-buttons.summary: The MouseEvent.buttons read-only property indicates which buttons are pressed on the mouse (or other input device) when a mouse event is triggered.
dom-mouseevent-buttons.title: MouseEvent.buttons

dom-mouseevent-relatedtarget.name: relatedTarget
dom-mouseevent-relatedtarget.summary: The MouseEvent.relatedTarget read-only property is the secondary target for the mouse event, if there is one. That is:
dom-mouseevent-relatedtarget.title: MouseEvent.relatedTarget

interface-mouseevent.name: MouseEvent
interface-mouseevent.summary: The MouseEvent interface represents events that occur due to the user interacting with a pointing device (such as a mouse). Common events using this interface include click, dblclick, mouseup, mousedown.
interface-mouseevent.title: MouseEvent

interface-wheelevent.name: WheelEvent
interface-wheelevent.summary: The WheelEvent interface represents events that occur due to the user moving a mouse wheel or similar input device.
interface-wheelevent.title: WheelEvent

event-type-load.name: load_event
event-type-load.summary: The load event is fired when the whole page has loaded, including all dependent resources such as stylesheets and images. This is in contrast to DOMContentLoaded, which is fired as soon as the page DOM has been loaded, without waiting for resources to finish loading.
event-type-load.title: Window: load event
